{{Infobox political party |name = Anti PowerPoint Party |lang1 = [[German language|German]] |name_lang1 = Anti PowerPoint Partei |lang2 = [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]] |name_lang2 = Parti Anti PowerPoint |logo = |colorcode = #ff0000 |founder = Matthias Poehm |leader1_title = President |leader1_name = Matthias Poehm |slogan = ''Finally do something!'' |founded = 2011 |headquarters = [[Bonstetten, Switzerland|Bonstetten]], [[Switzerland]] |ideology = Opposition to [[presentation software]] |website = [http://www.anti-powerpoint-party.com/ Anti PowerPoint Party] |country = Switzerland |footnotes = }}The '''Anti PowerPoint Party''' (APPP) is a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[political party]] dedicated to decreasing professional use of [[Microsoft PowerPoint]] and other [[presentation software]], which the party claims "causes national-economic damage amounting to 2.1 billion [[Swiss franc|CHF]]" and lowers the quality of a presentation in "95 % of the cases".<ref name="cause">{{cite web | url=http://www.anti-powerpoint-party.com/the-cause/ |title=The Cause |publisher=Anti PowerPoint Party |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> The party advocates [[flip chart]]s as an alternative to presentation software.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17852_3-20076872-71/swiss-political-party-tries-to-ban-powerpoint/ |title=Swiss political party tries to ban PowerPoint |first=Chris |last=Matyszczyk |work=[[CNET]] |date=July 5, 2011 | accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref>
APPP was formed by former software engineer Matthias Poehm ahead of the [[Swiss federal election, 2011|2011 federal elections]] in Switzerland.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/aug/28/powerpoint-party-switzerland-ban |title=The political party that wants to ban PowerPoint |first=Julie |last=Bindel |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=August 28, 2011 |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> The party's goal is to become the fourth largest party in Switzerland in terms of membership, and to initiate a national "[[referendum]] in order to seek for a prohibition of PowerPoint [and other presentation software] during presentations."<ref name="cause"/> APPP states that it does not support prohibition, but will use a referendum to raise awareness about the cause.<ref name="cause"/>
