{{Infobox COA case | Litigants = New York State Restaurant Association v. New York City Board of Health | Court = [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] | ArgueDate = | ArgueYear = | DecideDate = Pending | DecideYear = | FullName = New York State Restaurant Association v. New York City Board of Health | Citations = | Prior = | Subsequent = | Holding = Pending | Judges = | Majority = | JoinMajority = | Concurrence = | JoinConcurrence = | Dissent = | JoinDissent = | LawsApplied = | italic title = force }} {{update|date=November 2010}} '''''New York State Restaurant Association v. New York City Board of Health''''' is a case decided by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second Circuit United States Court of Appeals]]. The case arose after New York City passed a law in January 2007 to become the first American city to require [[restaurant chains]] to state the number of [[calories]] in everything on their menus. The [[National Restaurant Association|New York State Restaurant Association]] (NYSRA) sued, arguing infringement of commercial freedom of speech under the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]].<ref name = "econ">{{cite journal | date = August 28, 2008 | title = Menu items Restaurant chains must now list the calorie content of the food they sell | journal = [[The Economist]] | url = http://www.economist.com/business/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12010393 }}</ref> The NYSRA also argued that the [[Nutrition Labeling and Education Act]] (NLEA) of 1990<ref name="law">21 U.S.C. §§ 301, et seq., ("NLEA")</ref> and FDA regulations [[Wiktionary:preempt|preempted]] New York's calorie posting regulation.<ref name="doc">{{cite journal|title=Food Labeling |journal=American Medical Association |url=http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/category/17845.html#New_York_Restaurant_Assoc |format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AFood+Labeling&as_publication=American+Medical+Association&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517032508/http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/category/17845.html |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref> The Second Circuit rejected all of the Restaurant Association's claims and upheld the New York City law. Congressman [[Henry Waxman]], who was the NLEA's chief sponsor, joined an [[amicus brief]] in support of New York City's position and was represented by Public Citizen Litigation Group.<ref name="wax">{{cite journal | title =New York State Restaurant Association (NYSRA) v. New York Department of Health, et al. | journal = Public Citizen | url = http://www.citizen.org/litigation/forms/cases/CaseDetails.cfm?cID=420 }}</ref>
