{{Infobox election | election_name = South African general election, 1970 | country = South Africa | flag_year = 1961 | flag_image = | type = Parliamentary | vote_type = Popular <!-- default --> | ongoing = no | party_colour = | party_name = | previous_election = South African general election, 1966 | previous_year = 1966 | previous_mps = | election_date = {{Start date|1970|4|22|df=y}} | elected_mps = | next_election = South African general election, 1974 | next_year = 1974 | next_mps = | seats_for_election= All 166 seats in the [[House of Assembly of South Africa|House of Assembly]] | majority_seats = | opinion_polls = | turnout = <!-- person 1 --> | image1 = [[File:John Vorster.jpg|97px]] | colour1 = | leader1 = [[B. J. Vorster]] | party1 = National Party (South Africa) | leader_since1 = | leaders_seat1 = | last_election1 = 126 seats | seats_before1 = | seats_needed1 = | seats1 = 118 | seats_after1 = | seat_change1 = {{decrease}}8 <!-- any --> | popular_vote1 = 820,968 | percentage1 = 54.43% | swing1 = {{decrease}}3.88% <!-- person 2 --> | image2 = [[File:Sir De Villiers Graaff.jpg|x130px]] | colour2 = | leader2 = [[De Villiers Graaff]] | party2 = United Party (South Africa) | alliance2 = <!-- legislative or parliamentary --> | leader_since2 = | leaders_seat2 = | last_election2 = 39 seats | seats_before2 = | seats_needed2 = | seats2 = 47 | seats_after2 = | seat_change2 = {{increase}}8 <!-- any --> | popular_vote2 = 561,647 | percentage2 = 37.23% | swing2 = {{decrease}}0.14% <!-- bottom --> | title = Prime Minister | before_election = [[B. J. Vorster]] | before_party = National Party (South Africa) | posttitle = | after_election = [[B. J. Vorster]] | after_party = National Party (South Africa) | map_image = South African House of Assembly 1970.svg | map_size = 300px | map_caption = House of Assembly after the election }} {{Politics of South Africa}} The '''1970 South African general election''' was held on 22 April for the 166-seat [[House of Assembly of South Africa|House of Assembly]]. Parliament was dissolved on 2 March and the deadline for the submission of candidates was 13 March. This was the first time in South African history that the House elected was responsible entirely to [[White South African|white people]], as the seats of the four MPs elected separately by "qualified" [[Cape Coloured]] expired in the same year.
The [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] (NP) won another election, for the first time under the leadership of [[John Vorster]]. Several new representatives were elected, including [[Chris Heunis]], future Acting President and [[Pik Botha]], future [[Minister of Foreign Affairs]] for 17 years, who made his maiden speech demanding that the government sign the [[UN Declaration of Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.litera.co.za/pikeng.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001181359/http://www.litera.co.za/pikeng.htm |archivedate=1 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
However, the NP lost some support in parliament for the first time since the [[South African general election, 1948|1948 election]], its number of seats being reduced by eight. This could be attributed to losing votes to the right-wing splinter [[Herstigte Nasionale Party]] (Reconstituted National Party). While it did not win any seats, the split in the nationalist voter base benefitted the main opposition [[United Party (South Africa)|United Party]] (UP) in some constituencies.
[[Helen Suzman]], [[member of parliament]] for [[Houghton Estate, Gauteng|Houghton]], retained her seat as the sole representative of the [[Liberalism|liberal]] [[Progressive Party (South Africa)|Progressive Party]].
==House of Assembly results == Elections were held in 155 of the 166 constituencies (11 members elected unopposed). There were 2 028 487 registered voters and 1 508 248 votes were cast (74.7% of voters in contested constituencies).<ref>IPU http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/arc/SOUTH_AFRICA_1970_E.PDF</ref>
